observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the LCE direct the MA to: 

Properly adjust the final budgets of the affected accounts to determine the proper amount of savings under MOOE and continuing appropriations of the incoming year’s financial statements; 

Thereafter, present properly the changes in the approved budget as supported by supplemental budget;


Strictly prepare and maintain the required Registry of Appropriation, Allotment and Obligation (RAAOs) for each service, funds, and PPAs; and

Conduct periodic reconciliation of working schedules and RAAOs with the records of the Budget Office.

We recommended that the LCE direct the Municipal Agriculturist and MPDC to

Include PPAs under RA No. 7171 share for the furtherance of the tobacco industry in the LGU, and;


Maximize the 25%  allocation of the total share for cooperative programs, livelihood projects, and financial support for registered tobacco farmers to ensure optimal use of the RA No. 7171 share of the Municipality.

We recommended that the LCE direct the MA to:
Stop the practice of waiting for payment of retention money before submitting the vouchers related to the payment of contractors and supplier;
Immediately submit the identified vouchers or transactions to the audit team, henceforth, to submit all disbursement vouchers within the 10th day at the end of each following month as required under the above Circular.

We recommended that the LCE direct the AAO and MA to:
Coordinate with other responsible offices to ensure the immediate updating and regular reconciliation of employee records with GSIS, Pag-IBIG, and PhilHealth to prevent discrepancies, ensure accurate remittances, and safeguard employees' eligibility for benefits;
Designate personnel specifically assigned to handle GSIS, PhilHealth, and Pag-IBIG transactions. These personnel shall be responsible for monitoring and updating contributions and remittances, addressing related concerns, and facilitating the effective dissemination of relevant updates and issuances from the concerned agencies. They shall also coordinate with the MA for the timely reconciliation of financial records and reports;
Conduct a regular review of the monthly premiums deducted from payroll/disbursement vouchers for remittance to GSIS, Pag-IBIG and PhilHealth, and ensure that amounts withheld are consistent with the amounts required to be remitted monthly; and
Strictly abide with the provisions of Section 5(c) of RA 8291, Sections 6(a) and 3(e) of Rule VII of IRR of RA No. 9769, and Section 19(d) of Title III Rule III of the Revised IRR of RA 7875, to avoid administrative sanctions.

We recommended that the LCE direct the:
MA to ensure that no DV shall be accepted or processed by the Accounting Office unless it is accompanied by a duly accomplished Procurement Document Checklist, duly signed by the BAC Secretariat;
BAC Secretariat to immediately implement proper documentation procedures, particularly the consistent indication of date of receipt on all procurement-related documents submitted to their office;
BAC to:
Review and improve its internal validation process during bid opening, evaluation, and post-qualification to ensure that only bidders who fully comply with documentary and technical requirements are declared eligible and awarded contracts; and
Ensure that a pre-procurement conference is conducted for all procurements where the ABC exceeds ₱2,000,000.00 for goods, ₱5,000,000.00 for infrastructure projects, and ₱1,000,000.00 for Consulting Services. This conference shall verify that the procurement aligns with the approved PPMP and APP, and confirm the procuring entity’s readiness regarding legal, technical, and financial requirements.

We recommended that the LCE direct the GFP to:

Reinforce the preparation of the GAD Plan and Budget with a more prudent gender analysis through establishing the cause/s of identified gender issues and thereafter formulate the PPA/s that directly address the same, and;

Establish the Municipality’s GAD Database to strengthen data gathering and identification of implementable GAD PPAs.

We have recommended that the LCE direct the Municipal Engineer to:

Ascertain the actual completion of the five projects by showing records of actual inspection conducted such as geo-tagged photos and revised accordingly, the actual completion date as a result of validation;

Compute liquidated damages, if warranted;



Submit Notice of Extension of Contracts and its supporting documents

6.10. We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the Municipal
Treasurer to:

a. Prepare and maintain cashbooks and submit immediately to the audit
team for verification and examination;

b. Prepare and submit the RAAF for CY 2021 and for the ensuing years;

c. Require the collectors to remit all collections daily and to prepare the
RCR in acknowledging the remittance;

d. Deposit daily and intact all collections; and

e. Deposit immediately the unaccounted amount of ₱37,944.89.

In view of the foregoing, we have recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the Acting Municipal Treasurer to:

Perform religiously the verification process of collection and accountable forms of its collectors upon their remittance;



Cause the immediate remittance of collections not yet turned-over to her and for the collectors to observe the practice of remitting all collections daily;





Submit monthly and consolidated RAAF for period of January to December, 2019; and




Update her cashbooks daily and reconcile with records of the Municipal Accountant.

We have recommended that the Local Chief Executive direct the Municipal Accountant to:

Prepare the journals using the prescribed format as provided under the NGAS Manual;

Prepare and submit monthly trial balances and quarterly and year-end financial statements on time; 



Use the correct accounts to fairly present in the financial statements; and



Exert utmost effort to reconcile the inter-agency receivables/payables and prepare the necessary adjusting entries to present the accurate balances.



Thereafter, based on the reconciliation statement made by the Municipal Accountant, we recommended that the Municipal Mayor instruct the Municipal Treasurer to transfer the actual cash to the specific fund where it really belongs, if necessary to avoid accumulation of fund balances.

We recommended that Municipal Mayor direct the Municipal Accountant to:
Use the journals prescribed by the NGAS Manual which includes the CkDJ, CDJ, CRJ and GJ;
Submit all the GL of all the accounts presented in the financial statements;
Review the entries in the GL and should coincide with the journals. Adjustment shall be made whether in the GL or journal, where appropriate. Adjust the financial statements, if necessary; and
Assess the need to have an electronic system in generating financial statements of the LGU and if it warrants, use the prescribed accounting system which is the eNGAS.
The Municipal Accountant explained that that the amounts of ₱175,428.50 and ₱11,073.00 recognized as settlement of Accounts Payable were presented in the GL as settlement of Due to Officers and Employees and failed to correct the entry in the CkDJ. He expressed that he is considering the eNGAS system if budget of the LGU warrants its availability.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the Municipal Engineer to:
Ascertain the actual completion of the five projects by showing records of actual inspection conducted such as geo-tagged photos and revised accordingly, the actual completion date as a result of validation;
Compute liquidated damages, if warranted
Submit Inspection Reports of PPAs reported in the GPPA Report;
Submit Notice of Extension of Contracts and its supporting documents
During the exit conference, the Municipal Engineer has not provided details with the deficiencies noted since he has to recall or review the documents of the project. Nonetheless, it was explained that the failure of immediate payment to the contractor upon completion of projects was contributed to the factor of occurrence of pandemic.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
Direct the Building to Official to a) provide status on those issued building permits without occupancy permits and impose necessary fees for completed projects, and thereafter, monitor those issued with building permits to secure occupancy permits first before actually occupying the structures constructed; b) submit the building permits and occupancy permits issued per month to the Municipal Assessor in order to be used as basis for assessment and updating of the Assessment Roll;
Tap the Barangay Officials to report to Building Official monthly/quarterly the on-going construction and completed structures in their barangays in order to facilitate the Building Official in monitoring compliance of the structures with the National Building Code of the Philippines and maximize income generated therewith;
Enjoin the Municipal Engineer to religiously monitor newly constructed buildings, whether commercial or residential; and
Direct the Municipal Assessor to verify whether real properties within the municipality are properly listed in the assessment rolls specifically those newly constructed or renovated.
The Municipal Building Official assured the Audit team to strictly comply with the provisions of the Building Code. The office shall revisit the previously issued building permits and conduct actual inspection of said projects to ensure compliance to the approved construction specifications and plans. Accordingly, occupancy certificates shall be issued for completed projects and especially those which were previously assessed and collected occupancy fees. Likewise, the office committed to forward a monthly report of issued building and occupancy permits to the Municipal Assessor which will serve as reference in conducting property assessment.

In view of the foregoing, we have recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the Acting Municipal Treasurer to:
Perform religiously the verification process of collection and accountable forms of its collectors upon their remittance;
Cause the immediate remittance of collections not yet turned-over to her and for the collectors to observe the practice of remitting all collections daily;
Submit monthly and consolidated RAAF for period of January to December, 2019; and
Update her cashbooks daily and reconcile with records of the Municipal Accountant.

We have recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the ICO-Municipal Treasurer to:

Cause the collecting officers to remit their collections daily and intact;

Stop the practice of accommodating checks using the cash collections;

Establish  proper control in handling receipts and deposits of collections of the municipality, specifically, maintaining records of each collector’s accountability for accountable forms;

Submit  Monthly Consolidated Report of Accountability of Accountable Forms for the period January to December, 2018; and

Update his cashbooks daily and to reconcile with the records of the accounting.

We have also recommended that the Municipal Accountant to properly monitor the recording of receipts and deposits of the municipality and to reflect adjustments, if any based on the above-mentioned observations.

We have  recommended that the Local Chief Executive direct the Municipal Accountant to:

Prepare  the journals using the prescribed format as provided under the NGAS Manual; 

Prepare  and submit monthly trial balances and quarterly and year-end financial statements on time;

Use  the correct accounts to fairly present in the financial statements; and

Exert utmost effort to reconcile the inter-agency receivables/payables and prepare the necessary adjusting entries to present the accurate balances.

Thereafter, based on the reconciliation statement made by the Municipal Accountant, we recommended that the Municipal Mayor instruct the Municipal Treasurer to transfer the actual cash to the specific fund where it really belongs, if necessary to avoid accumulation of fund balances.

We have recommended that Management:

Comply with the additional requirements for submission to NSWMC for the approval of the Municipality’s Ten-Year Solid Waste Management Plan; 

Strictly implement and monitor “No Segregation, No Collection” policy. The LGU to partner with barangay personnel to monitor every household;

Fully utilize the MRFs and strictly follow the schedule of garbage collection with regard to biodegradable, non-biodegradable and recyclables likewise be strictly implemented; and

Impose penalty to violators to gather income to support projects and activities related to solid waste management.
